00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:57.145
are out there in the public
discourse, in the media,

00:01:57.145 --> 00:01:59.410
and what people
are talking about.

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:01.990
And we then realized that,
indeed, really health wellness

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:03.610
is quite broadly
defined, when we

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.200
think about the interaction
of gender and sport.

00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:09.610
And it encompasses concepts
like gender disparities

00:02:09.610 --> 00:02:12.670
in common sports injuries,
like ACL tears and concussions,

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:13.870
for example--

00:02:13.870 --> 00:02:15.700
both in terms of
their incidence,

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:17.650
or how much they
happen, but also

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:20.950
how they're treated, so,
who ends up having surgery

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:23.650
or not after an ACL
tear, and who returns

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:26.140
to play after a concussion.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:29.800
And it's more likely that
in this post-Title-IX boom,

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:32.770
with over three million
high school girls competing

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:35.320
in sports, as was
noted this morning,

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.920
that these topics are going to
become more and more important.

00:02:38.920 --> 00:02:43.270
How we address treatment and
issues related to sports injury

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:45.820
according to gender is going
to become even more important

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:47.290
over time.

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:49.270
It also encompasses
the impact of gender

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:53.080
on youth sport participation
as a measure of wellness.

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:55.420
And, you know, these days,
the childhood obesity rate

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:57.220
is estimated at up to 30%.

00:02:57.220 --> 00:03:00.190
So, when we think about
how gender impacts things

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:03.400
like implicit bias and
unconscious perceptions of who

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:06.580
we expect to be active,
who do we expect to engage

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:09.760
in physical activity in sport
as a means of healthy lifestyles

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.980
as they move into
adulthood, we can

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:14.620
see that that is a critical
component of when we think

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:16.300
about health and wellness.

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:18.430
And last but not least,
in our elite athletes,

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:20.380
how much is too much?

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:22.810
And we know that athletes
often feel the pressure to win

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:26.080
at all costs, despite the
potential for adverse health

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:28.720
outcomes, related to things
like packed competition

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:32.140
schedules, over-training,
and even when athletes

00:03:32.140 --> 00:03:33.880
are tempted to cross
the line into use

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.590
of performance-enhancing
substances,

00:03:35.590 --> 00:03:40.100
and prohibited methods,
and other mechanisms.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:42.520
So we're thrilled to host
these three esteemed panelists

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:44.936
to help us work through some
of these challenging and very

00:03:44.936 --> 00:03:47.962
timely themes all related
to health and wellness.

00:03:47.962 --> 00:03:49.420
And each of these
three individuals

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.220
