00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.040
So, I'm the chief
medical officer

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.969
of the NCAA, the first
chief medical officer.

00:07:14.969 --> 00:07:17.260
I've been at his job for a
little more than four years.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:19.760
The NCAA, for those
of you who don't know,

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:22.600
is the governing body
of college varsity

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:26.470
sports for 1,100 schools,
500,000 student athletes.

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:28.150
We were formed in 1906.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:29.620
Really, it was
President Roosevelt

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:32.890
at the time who decided that we
needed to have a governing body

00:07:32.890 --> 00:07:36.765
to really oversee football
because there were 18 football

00:07:36.765 --> 00:07:38.140
deaths the year
before, and there

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:39.480
was an existential crisis.

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:43.120
So, flash forward, 90% of my
headaches for the 23 sports

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:46.330
and 90 championships that
we oversee is football.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:49.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:49.230 --> 00:07:51.870
The NCAA is a
membership-driven organization.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:52.890
It's bottom-up.

00:07:52.890 --> 00:07:54.390
So, when we read
in the newspaper,

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:57.300
the NCAA didn't do this,
the NCAA didn't do that--

00:07:57.300 --> 00:07:59.410
it's the membership.

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:02.130
We are the opposite of
top-down organizations,

00:08:02.130 --> 00:08:05.241
such as the NFL and
the Catholic church.

00:08:05.241 --> 00:08:07.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:07.890 --> 00:08:10.125
I have no disclosures.

00:08:10.125 --> 00:08:13.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:13.850 --> 00:08:15.720
Although I did go to Notre Dame.

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:19.190
So, there's a
Catholic disclosure.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:22.640
I'm going to just give a very,
very brief overview of things

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:24.830
that I believe are
pertinent to the NCAA

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:27.110
because, after all,
that's my world.

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:29.210
We won't take a deep
dive into any of these.

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:31.800
We really don't have the time.

00:08:31.800 --> 00:08:33.440
So, let's look at
participation rates.

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:35.120
We've talked about this briefly.

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:37.520
And we could look and say,
wow, participation rates

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.820
for women's sports have really
been increasing considerably

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:41.679
over the years.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:42.950
And, yay, Title IX.

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:44.620
And, yay, society.

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:46.490
We're really getting
our act together.

00:08:46.490 --> 00:08:49.460
And when we talk to the
women who are in sport,

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.160
they get a lot out of it.

00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:55.460
They really love being athletes.

00:08:55.460 --> 00:08:58.610
And it drives them for
the rest of their life.

00:08:58.610 --> 00:09:01.930
And so it is a reason
to truly celebrate.

00:09:01.930 --> 00:09:05.240
But we can look at these same
statistics and say, well,

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.580
is this a reason to celebrate?

00:09:06.580 --> 00:09:08.530
Or is this a reason to
look at our barriers?

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:11.290
Because, well, look at this.

00:09:11.290 --> 00:09:14.140
Yes, there has been a great
increase in women participation

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:14.980
in sport.

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:18.520
But also, for all those
naysayers of Title IX,

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:20.410
look at the growth
in men's sport.

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:23.930
Title IX has done nothing
to diminish that growth.

00:09:23.930 --> 00:09:26.900
And look at the more recent
statistics about women

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:28.880
in college compared to men.

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:32.030
And they are the majority,
but the statistics

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:34.430
are more than reversed
for women participation

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:35.750
in college sports.

00:09:35.750 --> 00:09:37.760
So, there is still a gap.

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:41.340
There are barriers
that still exist.

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:43.920
I want to talk a little bit
about one aspect of sport

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:46.980
injury that we've heard a lot
about, and that is concussion.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:48.510
And I will say very clearly--

00:09:48.510 --> 00:09:51.000
I've said this publicly
on many occasions--

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.670
concussion is the
elephant in the room.

00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:57.540
But the single most
important aspect

00:09:57.540 --> 00:10:01.230
of care that we need to address
for our student athletes

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:02.980
is mental health.

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:06.930
The student athletes have told
me that, time and time again.

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.540
And I've visited over 100
schools, including Harvard,

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:11.760
and I meet with the
student athletes.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:14.380
This is their number 1 concern.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:15.550
But what about concussion?

00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:16.970
So, we hear about concussion.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:18.790
We hear about football.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:20.680
And this is a study,
it was actually

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:22.630
published just recently.

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:24.880
And the rate of
concussion is determined

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:26.590
by athletic exposures.

00:10:26.590 --> 00:10:29.200
The highest-risk sport
for rate of concussion

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:30.730
is men's wrestling.

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:32.440
But look at the
four women's sports

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:35.410
that have virtually the same
rate of concussion as men's

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:36.580
football--

00:10:36.580 --> 00:10:41.050
women's soccer, women's ice
hockey, women's basketball,

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:42.970
woman's lacrosse.

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:45.910
Now you should be shocked
that women's lacrosse is there

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:47.570
because the rules
of woman lacrosse

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:50.545
is that this is a
non-contact sport.

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:55.150
Well, what about concussion?

00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:57.980
For every single major
aspect of health and safety,

00:10:57.980 --> 00:11:00.010
we must do a gap analysis.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:02.050
And the real gap analysis
is that we don't even

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:04.490
know the natural
history of concussion.

00:11:04.490 --> 00:11:06.940
We have no idea what
neurobiological recovery

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:08.140
is in concussion.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:10.870
And we know very
little about women

00:11:10.870 --> 00:11:13.840
who get concussed
because 95% of the world

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:16.750
literature on concussion
is dominated by men's

00:11:16.750 --> 00:11:19.270
football and men's ice hockey.

00:11:19.270 --> 00:11:21.250
So, when we have a gap
analysis like that,

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:22.930
we have to take action.

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:24.550
We have to advocate.

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:27.220
The NCAA partnered with
the Department of Defense,

00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:29.890
and we have put together the
largest prospective clinical

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:33.220
longitudinal study ever done
in the history of concussion.

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:36.250
It's currently with 30
schools, and our recent data

00:11:36.250 --> 00:11:39.790
tell us that we've now
analyzed over 30,000 athletes.

00:11:39.790 --> 00:11:41.820
We've tracked 2,000 concussions.

00:11:41.820 --> 00:11:43.780
And we're taking an
exceptionally deep dive

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:46.250
into several
high-contact, risk sports,

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:48.900
including women's ice hockey,
women's soccer, women's

00:11:48.900 --> 00:11:51.910
lacrosse, where the athletes
are wearing had accelerometers.

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:54.540
They're getting genetic testing
blood biomarkers, genomics,

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:55.780
and brain MRIs.

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:59.110
So, we are going to understand
the neurobiology of concussion.

00:11:59.110 --> 00:12:01.540
I will say that of these
2,000 concussed athletes

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:03.940
we've studied, 40% are women.

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:07.920
A large study
before that was 20%.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:09.570
It's an exceptionally
intense study.

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:11.490
I won't go into
the details of it.

00:12:11.490 --> 00:12:14.190
But athletes are
tested at baseline

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:17.790
and then at subsequent
intervals over six months.

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:22.170
On average, most athletes return
to play after a concussion

00:12:22.170 --> 00:12:23.940
by three weeks.

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:26.760
If we sort that out-- and this
is not yet published data.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:29.151
It has not been vetted in
peer-reviewed literature.

00:12:29.151 --> 00:12:30.900
And by the way, in all
the literature that

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:32.370
is going to come
from this study,

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:34.380
I will only be on the
first two studies,

00:12:34.380 --> 00:12:36.150
the methodological studies.

00:12:36.150 --> 00:12:38.820
I will not be part of
any of the data analysis.

00:12:38.820 --> 00:12:40.770
And these studies are
being run independently

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:42.420
by our member schools.

00:12:42.420 --> 00:12:45.590
But the athletes that return
the quickest after a concussion

00:12:45.590 --> 00:12:48.771
are our contact-sport athletes.

00:12:48.771 --> 00:12:50.520
I'm not going to give
you the why of that.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:51.580
We can talk about that.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:53.400
We can hypothesize about that.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:55.170
But it's the non-contact
sport athletes

00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:57.870
that take the longest
to return to play.

00:12:57.870 --> 00:13:01.470
And women, in general,
are taking two days longer

00:13:01.470 --> 00:13:02.310
to play--

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:04.650
to return to play, after
a concussion than men.

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:06.600
I will tell you
right off the bat,

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:09.540
women concuss
differently than men--

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:14.350
neurophysiologically
and biomechanically.

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:16.270
That's just a fact.

00:13:16.270 --> 00:13:19.540
It's not a statement of saying
women and men do mathematics

00:13:19.540 --> 00:13:20.560
differently.

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:23.160
It's saying that women
concuss differently.

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:25.300
And part of it, in
childbearing ages,

00:13:25.300 --> 00:13:27.130
is because of the
profound influence

00:13:27.130 --> 00:13:30.010
of estradiol, which prepares
the woman every month

00:13:30.010 --> 00:13:34.430
to receive a fertilized egg.

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:36.380
And that has a
profound effect on what

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:38.720
we call spreading ways
of electrical depression

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.600
in brain activity, which is
one of the pathophysiologic

00:13:41.600 --> 00:13:45.290
mechanisms of migraine and
also for a prolonged concussion

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:46.700
recovery.

00:13:46.700 --> 00:13:49.910
Women, in general, also,
they have more symptoms

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:51.860
to report than men.

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:53.810
These are just facts.

00:13:53.810 --> 00:13:56.180
And at some point, we are
going to take a deep dive

00:13:56.180 --> 00:13:57.010
into the why.

00:14:00.070 --> 00:14:01.930
Moving to sexual
violence, the NCAA

00:14:01.930 --> 00:14:05.200
has put out just recently the
Sexual Violence Prevention Tool

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:06.010
Kit.

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:08.710
Every member school
has this toolkit.

00:14:08.710 --> 00:14:12.430
It has been endorsed by 12
higher education organizations.

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:15.310
And our goal is to
widely socialize this.

00:14:15.310 --> 00:14:18.250
The Board of Governors, who is
the highest ranking committee

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:20.580
for the NCAA made
of 16 presidents,

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:22.720
they just appointed
a special commission

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:25.000
to look deeper into
this, and to come up

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.550
with policy that will be
independent of Title IX

00:14:27.550 --> 00:14:28.390
and Clery.

00:14:28.390 --> 00:14:30.200
Why?

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:34.380
Because Clery, as we know
it, may be gone soon.

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:38.280
Violence Against Women Act,
as we know it, may be gone.

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:40.710
Title IX may shift to
the Department of Justice

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:42.480
from the Department
of Education.

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:46.350
We must be actively
prepared for the future.

00:14:46.350 --> 00:14:49.770
And we are addressing
this with sexual violence.

00:14:49.770 --> 00:14:55.440
Looking at a recent study that
looked over 25,000 college

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:56.370
students--

00:14:56.370 --> 00:14:59.340
so the rate of sexual
violence, even in one year,

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:02.790
it varies from school to school,
but it is still astoundingly

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:05.105
high up to 20% in some schools.

00:15:05.105 --> 00:15:06.480
And we will look
at these college

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:09.600
students and their lifetime
incidents of sexual violence.

00:15:09.600 --> 00:15:12.010
It's astoundingly high.

00:15:12.010 --> 00:15:14.590
This is part of our society.

00:15:14.590 --> 00:15:16.600
This is humanity.

00:15:16.600 --> 00:15:19.660
This is Homo sapiens.

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:22.090
And when we look at
those individuals

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:24.820
and talk to those individuals
who have been victims,

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:28.900
they are much more likely to
be hopeless, to be depressed,

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:32.920
and to actually suffer with
psychiatric conditions.

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:34.540
And I'll just take
a pause right now

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:36.940
because I have treated
thousands of victims

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:40.030
of the most horrendous sexual
and interpersonal violence

00:15:40.030 --> 00:15:41.480
ever.

00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:45.140
That was part of my
subspecialty as a neurologist--

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:47.960
working with
Holocaust survivors,

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:51.260
working with survivors of
other profound violence.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:54.540
And when you talk to
these individuals,

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:59.590
and you try to
understand, you realize

00:15:59.590 --> 00:16:04.250
that free will, as we
may hypothesize about it,

00:16:04.250 --> 00:16:06.470
as we may think
metaphysically about it--

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:09.800
it no longer exists.

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:12.950
It doesn't exist at the
moment of sexual violence

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:16.490
and from every
moment thereafter.

00:16:16.490 --> 00:16:19.490
Because it changes
your physiology.

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:22.130
It changes your
perception of life.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:24.680
And unless there is a
miraculous, neurobiological

00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:27.710
reconciliation,
peacefully, and almost

00:16:27.710 --> 00:16:29.780
with what we call
unconditional love,

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:33.520
your physiology is
forever changed.

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:34.975
Free will no longer exists.

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:41.120
Moving to some
lighter subjects--

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:42.374
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:45.280
--anterior cruciate
ligament tears,

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:51.580
we know that females have a
much higher rate of ACL tears

00:16:51.580 --> 00:16:52.990
than males.

00:16:52.990 --> 00:16:53.920
Why?

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:55.450
Well, there are a few reasons.

00:16:55.450 --> 00:16:57.910
But let's look at
the societal reasons

00:16:57.910 --> 00:16:59.530
and the neurobiological reasons.

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:02.890
Because an ACL tear is
not a mechanical issue.

00:17:02.890 --> 00:17:06.730
It's a neuromuscular,
maladaptive response.

00:17:06.730 --> 00:17:09.609
It is, when you look
at the women who

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:12.950
are landing in their
ready position,

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:15.160
and if they're landing
repetitively like this,

00:17:15.160 --> 00:17:17.410
with poor neuromuscular
control, that's

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:19.960
a profound stress on the ACL.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:22.569
It is not the proper
land, like this.

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:24.910
And when we have,
in our society,

00:17:24.910 --> 00:17:26.920
people who are
specializing in sport

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:28.300
before the age of puberty--

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:33.170
despite all of the data that
it is the wrong thing to do--

00:17:33.170 --> 00:17:35.350
and then, when you look at
what happens at puberty,

00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:37.660
and testosterone
takes over in men,

00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:40.540
and that goes right
to the muscles,

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:44.210
it gives the men an advantage.

00:17:44.210 --> 00:17:47.500
And when you have someone who is
highly specialized, who doesn't

00:17:47.500 --> 00:17:49.240
know how to land,
who doesn't have

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:51.940
testosterone receptors
in their muscular system,

00:17:51.940 --> 00:17:54.310
and you have a repetitive,
maladaptive response,

00:17:54.310 --> 00:17:56.380
you have data like this.

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:59.510
It is simply not acceptable.

00:17:59.510 --> 00:18:00.880
Now, we talked about tennis.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:02.590
I'm not going to go
through all of these.

00:18:02.590 --> 00:18:04.630
But the tennis injury
rates are similar.

00:18:04.630 --> 00:18:07.750
And I do agree,
tennis is not perfect.

00:18:07.750 --> 00:18:10.570
But we should study
tennis because it's

00:18:10.570 --> 00:18:12.880
pretty close to perfect.

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:15.320
You go to the US Open
tennis championships,

00:18:15.320 --> 00:18:17.290
and on any given
day or night, we

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:19.090
are paying equal
amounts of money,

00:18:19.090 --> 00:18:21.580
and the women are getting
equal amounts of pay,

00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:26.260
for the single largest annual
sporting event in the world.

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:29.110
But I won't talk
about tennis anymore,

00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:31.722
other than that, when
I visit every school--

00:18:31.722 --> 00:18:33.930
and I'm a former tennis
player, and I still compete--

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:35.490
I always meet with
the tennis team.

00:18:35.490 --> 00:18:38.160
And I tell them in silence,
behind closed doors

00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:40.410
that, yes, there
are 23 NCAA sports,

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:42.672
but tennis is definitely
the greatest sport.

00:18:42.672 --> 00:18:44.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:48.690
And what about what's
happening since Title IX?

00:18:48.690 --> 00:18:51.740
Who's overseeing all of this?

00:18:51.740 --> 00:18:56.440
Who's overseeing the
care of our women?

00:18:56.440 --> 00:18:59.110
Because it does
make a difference.

00:18:59.110 --> 00:19:03.090
Pre-Title IX, when we
looked at coaches, well,

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:05.080
women's athletics were
separate from men.

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:08.410
So, the vast, vast
majority-- close to 100%--

00:19:08.410 --> 00:19:11.930
of coaches for women's
teams were female.

00:19:11.930 --> 00:19:20.270
We've been stuck at about
between 40%, 45% for years.

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:23.100
Does it make sense?

00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:26.190
Well, ask this question--
does it make sense

00:19:26.190 --> 00:19:28.680
that we've been
stuck at this amount,

00:19:28.680 --> 00:19:33.970
at this rate of athletic
directors across the NCAA?

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:36.940
We should be as
complacent with this data

00:19:36.940 --> 00:19:39.370
as we are with the data
of the number of females

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:42.400
in the current President
Trump's cabinet,

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:45.100
or with the number of females
who have been president

00:19:45.100 --> 00:19:46.480
of the United States.

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:49.430
We cannot be complacent
with this data.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:52.570
The NCAA has recently sent
out a presidential pledge.

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:56.110
It has gone to the president
of every one of the 1,100 NCAA

00:19:56.110 --> 00:19:56.860
schools.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:03.650
And 75% have signed on to this
to make a concerted effort

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:09.550
to shift the gap for
diversity, for gender, for all

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:13.600
of the things that
truly matter to us.

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:16.750
So, that's my brief,
very brief overview

00:20:16.750 --> 00:20:21.700
of some various aspects of
gender issues and sport.

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:24.100
And I'm going to take
another giant step back

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:27.370
because I'm really
listening very carefully.

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:30.310
This first panel was nothing
short of exceptional.

00:20:30.310 --> 00:20:33.460
And again, I really thank you
from the bottom of my heart

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:36.200
for allowing me to be here
and to learn from you.

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:36.790
So, thank you.

